ecuperation of history, the negotiation of the rural and the urban, and the representation of gender - and considers the related stylistic issues of the affinities between cinematic expression and nostalgia, the city and phallocentrism. The study concludes with an analysis of the formal question of the narrator in film and literature, through an assessment of Buñuel's previously unacknowledged stylistic debt to Galdós as manifested in his adaptations of Nazarín and Tristana. SALLY FAULKNER is Lecturer in Hispanic Studies at the University of Exeter.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMotion pictureszSpain. 0aSpanish literaturevFilm adaptations. 0aSpanish literaturevTelevision adaptations. 0aSpanish literaturexFilm and video adaptations. 4aFilm & Theatre. 4aHispanic Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aAdaptations.  aBuñuel's Narrator.  aGaldós' Stylistic Debt.  aGender Representation.  aHistory of Spanish Cinema.  aNazarín.  aRecuperation of History.  aRural and Urban Negotiation.  aSpanish Cinema.  aStylistic Issues.  aText and Context.  aTristana.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781846152764?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846152764423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846152764/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles